node.text: A few months ago I got to live @pfpicardi ‘s dream and spend the morning with @jennifer.garner a woman I stalk on the internet for book recommendations, meditations, and, of course, pretend cooking show bread baking joy.  I am not even sure how we cut this code down to 6 mins because we talked for hours about everything from America history (what actually happened vs what get taught) to LA neighborhoods, to creating pipelines that help entrepreneurs scale their businesses to ALIAS, to @onceuponafarm (Memph’s fave snack), to her dreams of being a librarian.  This video is mostly about my children’s book What The Road Said tho.  Thank you Jen and thank you Mo for such wonderful morning and for all of your support and also to my @theconsciouskid family for supporting my kids book since before day one.  So much love for these folks ❤️

So @simondavidkinberg you’re telling me you created an alien invasion show that takes place all around the world and is 100 percent heart and soul? 

*jay-z voice* YOU CRAZY FOR THIS ONE !!

But seriously, I am so very lucky to have gotten to see a lot of this show as it was being made. It’s smart  and beautiful and exciting and most importantly FUN to watch (is anyone else in the mental place where you just can’t watch anything too depressing or stressful during covid? It’s like too much) 

Proud of my baby daddy.  Watching him write these episodes and bring this to life truly exploded my brain and inspired me so much. 

Counting down the days til it comes out this fall on @appletv

I haven’t gone live since my book tour in March but I couldn’t pass up the opportunity to talk about The American Families Plan with theeee Karine Jean-Pierre (is anyone as obsessed with her as I am?). 
It’s so important that we pay attention to the policies our political leaders create. When we make ourselves a part of the process in this way, we are much better at holding them accountable to our needs, understanding when they are  doing what they said they were going to do when they asked us to vote for them and where they may be coming up short.  I was especially interested in talking about this plan because it covers the Biden/Harris administration’s efforts to better support teachers, parents and caregivers (especially women as 2.5 million women had to drop out of the workforce during Covid), HBCUs, expanding nutrition in our school food programs, paid family leave, early childhood care and universal pre-k.  These are all so important. It takes a village to raise a child, this plan is an investment in the village. Link in bio to learn more and read it for yourself (it’s only 10 pages good people).

node.text:
I am missing touring my kid's book WHAT THE ROAD SAID.  There was only one talk that was not on IG live because we really wanted to do this one in person with these two amazing women.  On the day of my book release, two of my girlfriends and main go-tos for advice on all things @nicolerichie and @camerondiaz came over for wine (@avaline of course!) and to share stories on bravery,  mistakes, and some of their life lessons. I’m excited to share it here for anyone who missed the livestream. ❤️

Directed by bff @globaliza

P.S.  What The Road Said is on the New York Times Best Sellers list for the second week in a row.  Thank you.  I love y’all. Grateful forever and ever.

node.text: Tonight, when the day is over, take a minute for yourself and listen to this conversation with @alex_elle - it truly gave me life. When I asked her about bravery, I almost cried at her response, she said, “Raising children is brave. Raising children differently than I was raised is brave.” WHEEEWWWW y’all. I am so thankful I got to end my week with her words and wisdom. And thank you to our beloved indie book store @mahoganybooks for supporting our chat with a big stack of signed WHAT THE ROAD SAID BOOKS available now for purchase and shipping anywhere in the country.

node.text: When I wrote this a few years ago, it was inspired by a romantic relationship.  Since then, I have found that these words have served me in ways I never considered they could.  A relationship with “release” leads us to a deeper connection with peace and healing.  So much of why we cannot find peace is because of the blocks we are holding on to. So much of why we cannot allow our healing to flow is because of the pain and hurt we are clenching so deeply.  There are moments where I am doing something that is supposed to be relaxing like listening to a meditation or resting on the couch and I notice my hands are in fists.  Over the years, I have had to create a daily practice of dropping my shoulders, taking deep breaths, finding tension wherever it may be in my body and releasing it- even something as simple as opening my palms or moving my jaw around. A practice of release has created pathways out of anxiety and into healing (or at the very least calm) for me in moments I have needed it most in my life.  Sharing with you this kind Sunday incase you need these words or this practice.  This poem may have started as a way I was loving someone else by letting go but it has transformed into a way I became able to love myself better by letting go.  Life is funny like that.  And so beautiful.  I love you.

node.text: A few months ago I got to live @pfpicardi ‘s dream and spend the morning with @jennifer.garner a woman I stalk on the internet for book recommendations, meditations, and, of course, pretend cooking show bread baking joy.  I am not even sure how we cut this code down to 6 mins because we talked for hours about everything from America history (what actually happened vs what get taught) to LA neighborhoods, to creating pipelines that help entrepreneurs scale their businesses to ALIAS, to @onceuponafarm (Memph’s fave snack), to her dreams of being a librarian.  This video is mostly about my children’s book What The Road Said tho.  Thank you Jen and thank you Mo for such wonderful morning and for all of your support and also to my @theconsciouskid family for supporting my kids book since before day one.  So much love for these folks ❤️
